        {
          "title": "How Language Models Work",
          "slug": "how-language-models-work",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# How Language Models Work\n\nA language model does one thing: given some text, predict what comes next. It's the autocomplete on your phone, scaled to billions of parameters and trained on trillions of words. Understanding this single idea — **next-token prediction** — is the key to understanding everything about LLMs.\n\n## What Is a Language Model?\n\nA language model assigns a probability to a sequence of tokens. Given \"The cat sat on the\", a good model assigns high probability to \"mat\" and low probability to \"uranium\":\n\n```\nP(\"mat\"    | \"The cat sat on the\") = 0.12\nP(\"rug\"    | \"The cat sat on the\") = 0.08\nP(\"floor\"  | \"The cat sat on the\") = 0.06\nP(\"uranium\"| \"The cat sat on the\") = 0.0001\n```\n\n**Autoregressive generation** works by repeatedly sampling the next token and appending it. Each prediction is conditioned on everything that came before. The model doesn't \"think ahead\" — it generates one token at a time, left to right.\n\n## From Statistical to Neural Language Models\n\nEarly language models were **n-gram** models: count how often word sequences appear in a corpus and estimate probabilities from frequencies. \"cat sat on\" appearing 50 times with \"the\" following 30 of those gives P(\"the\"|\"cat sat on\") = 0.6.\n\n**Limitations**: n-grams can only look at a small fixed window (3-5 words), can't generalize to unseen combinations, and require enormous storage for large vocabularies.\n\nNeural language models replaced these with learned representations. An embedding layer converts tokens to vectors, a neural network processes them, and a final layer outputs a probability distribution over the entire vocabulary.\n\n## Temperature and Sampling\n\nThe model produces raw scores (**logits**) for each vocabulary token, converted to probabilities via softmax. The **temperature** parameter controls creativity:\n\n- **Temperature → 0** (greedy): Always pick the highest-probability token. Deterministic but repetitive.\n- **Temperature = 1**: Sample from the learned distribution. Diverse but can be incoherent.\n- **Temperature > 1**: Flatter distribution, more random.\n\n**Top-k sampling** restricts choices to the k most likely tokens. **Top-p (nucleus) sampling** picks from the smallest set of tokens whose cumulative probability exceeds p (e.g., 0.9). Most production LLMs use top-p.\n\n## Perplexity: Measuring Model Quality\n\n**Perplexity** is the standard metric for language model quality — intuitively, it's the average number of tokens the model is \"choosing between\" at each step:\n\n```\nPerplexity = exp(average cross-entropy loss)\n```\n\nLower is better. A perplexity of 20 means the model is as uncertain as choosing uniformly among 20 options.\n\n## Why Next-Token Prediction Is Surprisingly Powerful\n\nIt seems almost too simple — just predict the next word. But consider what you need to know to predict well: grammar and syntax, world knowledge, reasoning ability, and common sense. Training on trillions of tokens forces the model to develop rich internal representations of language and knowledge — not because it was told to, but because those representations help predict the next token better.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Intro to Large Language Models](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zjkBMFhNj_g) by Andrej Karpathy — a one-hour talk covering the big picture of what LLMs are, how they're trained, and where they're going.\n",
          "summary": "Language models predict the next token in a sequence, and this deceptively simple objective forces them to develop rich representations of language, knowledge, and reasoning.",
          "concepts": [
            "language model",
            "next-token prediction",
            "autoregressive generation",
            "temperature",
            "top-p sampling",
            "perplexity"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "zjkBMFhNj_g",
          "video_title": "Intro to Large Language Models | Andrej Karpathy",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Tokenization & Vocabulary",
          "slug": "tokenization-vocabulary",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Tokenization & Vocabulary\n\nBefore text reaches a language model, it must be broken into **tokens** — the atomic units the model reads and generates. Tokenization is one of the most underappreciated parts of the LLM stack, and getting it wrong has real consequences.\n\n## Why Not Just Use Words?\n\nWord-level tokenization seems natural but fails in practice:\n\n- **Vocabulary explosion**: English has ~170,000 words in active use, plus names, URLs, code, and multilingual text. A manageable vocabulary needs to be 32K-128K tokens.\n- **Out-of-vocabulary (OOV)**: Any word not in the vocabulary becomes an unknown token, losing all information.\n- **Morphology blindness**: \"run\", \"runs\", \"running\", \"runner\" are treated as completely unrelated tokens.\n\nCharacter-level tokenization solves OOV but creates very long sequences and loses word-level meaning.\n\n## Byte Pair Encoding (BPE)\n\n**BPE** (Sennrich et al., 2016) strikes the balance. Starting from individual characters, it iteratively merges the most frequent adjacent pair:\n\n```\nCorpus: \"low lower lowest\"\nStep 0: l o w   l o w e r   l o w e s t\nStep 1: lo w   lo w e r   lo w e s t     (merge l+o)\nStep 2: low    low e r    low e s t       (merge lo+w)\nStep 3: low    lowe r     lowe s t        (merge low+e)\n```\n\nAfter enough merges, common words become single tokens while rare words split into familiar subwords. \"tokenization\" might become [\"token\", \"ization\"] — both meaningful pieces.\n\n## Modern Tokenizers\n\n| Tokenizer | Used By | Approach |\n|-----------|---------|----------|\n| **BPE** | GPT-2/3/4, Llama | Merge frequent byte pairs |\n| **WordPiece** | BERT | Likelihood-based merging |\n| **SentencePiece** | T5, Llama | Treats text as raw bytes, language-agnostic |\n| **Unigram** | XLNet, ALBERT | Starts large, prunes by likelihood |\n\nGPT-4 uses ~100K BPE tokens. Llama 3 uses 128K. Larger vocabularies improve efficiency (fewer tokens per text) at the cost of a bigger embedding matrix.\n\n## Tokenization Quirks\n\nTokenization creates surprising LLM behaviors:\n\n**Math struggles**: \"123 + 456\" might tokenize as [\"123\", \" +\", \" 456\"] or [\"12\", \"3\", \" +\", \" 4\", \"56\"]. The model never sees individual digits consistently, making arithmetic unreliable.\n\n**Multilingual inequality**: Tokenizers trained primarily on English text are inefficient for other languages — the same sentence in Japanese might require 3× more tokens than in English, making inference more expensive.\n\n```python\nfrom transformers import AutoTokenizer\n\ntok = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(\"meta-llama/Llama-3-8B\")\ntokens = tok.encode(\"Hello, world!\")\nprint(tok.convert_ids_to_tokens(tokens))\n```\n\n## Special Tokens\n\nEvery tokenizer includes special tokens with reserved roles: `<s>` (beginning of sequence), `</s>` (end of sequence), `<pad>` (padding), and chat template delimiters like `<|im_start|>`. These tokens structure the input and control generation behavior.\n\n## Why Tokenization Matters\n\nUnderstanding tokenization explains many LLM quirks: context window limits are in tokens not words (~1.3 tokens per English word), pricing is per token, and edge cases in code, math, and multilingual tasks often trace back to how text was tokenized.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Let's build the GPT Tokenizer](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zduSFxRajkE) by Andrej Karpathy — a hands-on deep dive into building a BPE tokenizer from scratch. You'll never look at tokens the same way.\n",
          "summary": "Tokenization converts text into subword units using algorithms like BPE, and its design choices directly impact LLM capabilities, efficiency, and failure modes.",
          "concepts": [
            "tokenization",
            "byte pair encoding",
            "subword tokens",
            "vocabulary size",
            "special tokens"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "zduSFxRajkE",
          "video_title": "Let's build the GPT Tokenizer | Andrej Karpathy",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
      ]
