      "title": "The Attention Mechanism",
      "order_index": 1,
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "Self-Attention from Scratch",
          "slug": "self-attention",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Self-Attention from Scratch\n\nAttention is the core mechanism that makes Transformers — and by extension, all modern LLMs — work. This lesson builds self-attention from first principles.\n\n## The Intuition: Dynamic Routing\n\nIn a feed-forward network or RNN, information flows along fixed paths. **Attention** is different: it creates **input-dependent connections**. Each token dynamically decides which other tokens are relevant and pulls information from them.\n\nWhen processing \"The animal didn't cross the street because **it** was too tired\", the word \"it\" needs to attend to \"animal\" (not \"street\") to resolve the reference. Attention learns to make these connections.\n\n## Queries, Keys, and Values\n\nSelf-attention uses three projections of each input token:\n\n- **Query (Q)**: \"What am I looking for?\"\n- **Key (K)**: \"What do I contain?\"\n- **Value (V)**: \"What information do I provide?\"\n\nEach token's embedding is projected through three learned weight matrices:\n\n```python\nQ = x @ W_Q  # (seq_len, d_k)\nK = x @ W_K  # (seq_len, d_k)\nV = x @ W_V  # (seq_len, d_v)\n```\n\n## Computing Attention Scores\n\nThe attention score between two tokens is the **dot product** of one's query and the other's key. High score = high relevance:\n\n```python\nscores = Q @ K.T  # (seq_len, seq_len)\n```\n\nThis produces a square matrix where entry (i, j) measures how much token *i* should attend to token *j*.\n\n## Scaling and Softmax\n\nDot products can grow large in magnitude (proportional to √d_k), pushing softmax into regions with near-zero gradients. We scale down:\n\n```python\nscores = scores / math.sqrt(d_k)\nweights = F.softmax(scores, dim=-1)  # each row sums to 1\n```\n\nThe softmax converts raw scores into a probability distribution — each token distributes its \"attention budget\" across all other tokens.\n\n## The Weighted Sum\n\nEach token's output is a weighted sum of all value vectors:\n\n```python\noutput = weights @ V  # (seq_len, d_v)\n```\n\nA token that strongly attends to position 5 will have an output dominated by position 5's value vector.\n\n## Full Implementation\n\n```python\nimport torch\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\nimport math\n\ndef self_attention(x, W_Q, W_K, W_V):\n    Q = x @ W_Q\n    K = x @ W_K\n    V = x @ W_V\n    d_k = K.shape[-1]\n    scores = Q @ K.transpose(-2, -1) / math.sqrt(d_k)\n    weights = F.softmax(scores, dim=-1)\n    return weights @ V\n```\n\nIn ~10 lines, you have the mechanism powering GPT-4, Claude, and every modern LLM.\n\n## Causal Masking\n\nFor autoregressive language models (GPT-style), tokens must not attend to future tokens — that would leak the answer. A **causal mask** sets future positions to -∞ before softmax:\n\n```python\nmask = torch.triu(torch.ones(seq_len, seq_len), diagonal=1).bool()\nscores = scores.masked_fill(mask, float('-inf'))\n```\n\n## Why Self-Attention Beats RNNs\n\n| Property | RNN | Self-Attention |\n|----------|-----|----------------|\n| Long-range deps | Degrade over distance | Direct to any position |\n| Parallelization | Sequential (slow) | Fully parallel (fast) |\n| Computation | O(n) sequential steps | O(n²) parallel ops |\n| Gradient path | Through n timesteps | Direct (1 step) |\n\nThe O(n²) cost is attention's main weakness — but for sequences up to ~8K tokens, the parallelism advantage dominates.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Attention in transformers, visually explained](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eMlx5fFNoYc) by 3Blue1Brown — a beautiful visual walkthrough of how queries, keys, and values work, with geometric intuitions that make the math click.\n- [Attention? Attention!](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2018-06-24-attention/) by Lilian Weng — a thorough survey of attention mechanisms from Bahdanau through Transformers, with clear math and diagrams.\n",
          "summary": "Self-attention computes dynamic, input-dependent connections between all tokens using query-key-value projections and scaled dot-product scores.",
          "concepts": [
            "self-attention",
            "queries keys values",
            "scaled dot-product attention",
            "causal masking",
            "attention weights"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "eMlx5fFNoYc",
          "video_title": "Attention in transformers, visually explained | 3Blue1Brown",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Multi-Head Attention & Positional Encoding",
          "slug": "multi-head-attention",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Multi-Head Attention & Positional Encoding\n\nSingle-head attention computes one set of attention weights — one \"view\" of token relationships. Multi-head attention runs multiple attention operations in parallel, letting the model capture different types of relationships simultaneously.\n\n## Why Multiple Heads?\n\nA single attention head can only focus on one type of relationship. In \"The cat, which was black, sat on the mat\", different relationships matter:\n\n- **Syntactic**: \"cat\" → \"sat\" (subject-verb agreement)\n- **Adjectival**: \"cat\" → \"black\" (attribute binding)\n- **Positional**: \"sat\" → \"on\" → \"mat\" (spatial phrase)\n\nMultiple heads let the model attend to all of these simultaneously.\n\n## Multi-Head Attention\n\nSplit the model dimension into *h* smaller heads, each operating on d_model/h dimensions:\n\n```\nMultiHead(Q, K, V) = Concat(head₁, ..., headₕ) · W_O\nheadᵢ = Attention(Q·W_Qᵢ, K·W_Kᵢ, V·W_Vᵢ)\n```\n\n```python\nclass MultiHeadAttention(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, d_model, n_heads):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.n_heads = n_heads\n        self.d_head = d_model // n_heads\n        self.W_Q = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model)\n        self.W_K = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model)\n        self.W_V = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model)\n        self.W_O = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model)\n\n    def forward(self, x, mask=None):\n        B, L, D = x.shape\n        Q = self.W_Q(x).view(B, L, self.n_heads, self.d_head).transpose(1, 2)\n        K = self.W_K(x).view(B, L, self.n_heads, self.d_head).transpose(1, 2)\n        V = self.W_V(x).view(B, L, self.n_heads, self.d_head).transpose(1, 2)\n\n        scores = Q @ K.transpose(-2, -1) / math.sqrt(self.d_head)\n        if mask is not None:\n            scores = scores.masked_fill(mask, float('-inf'))\n        weights = F.softmax(scores, dim=-1)\n\n        out = (weights @ V).transpose(1, 2).contiguous().view(B, L, D)\n        return self.W_O(out)\n```\n\n## What Heads Learn\n\nResearch shows different heads specialize: **syntactic heads** track subject-verb agreement, **positional heads** attend to adjacent tokens, and **rare word heads** focus on infrequent but informative tokens. Not all heads are equally important — some can be pruned with minimal quality loss.\n\n## The Position Problem\n\nSelf-attention treats its input as a **set**, not a sequence. \"Dog bites man\" and \"man bites dog\" produce identical attention scores — the model has no notion of word order. We need to inject positional information.\n\n## Sinusoidal Positional Encoding (Original Transformer)\n\nThe original Transformer added fixed positional encodings using sine and cosine at different frequencies:\n\n```\nPE(pos, 2i)   = sin(pos / 10000^(2i/d_model))\nPE(pos, 2i+1) = cos(pos / 10000^(2i/d_model))\n```\n\nEach position gets a unique signature, and the sinusoidal pattern lets the model learn relative positions.\n\n## Rotary Position Embeddings (RoPE)\n\nMost modern LLMs use **RoPE** (Su et al., 2021), which encodes position directly into Q and K by rotating them in 2D subspaces. The dot product Q·K then naturally depends on the **relative** position between tokens, enabling better generalization to unseen sequence lengths through interpolation techniques (NTK-aware scaling, YaRN).\n\n## ALiBi: Attention with Linear Biases\n\n**ALiBi** (Press et al., 2022) takes the simplest approach: add a linear penalty to attention scores based on distance. No learned parameters — just a fixed bias. Each head uses a different slope, so some heads focus locally and others attend broadly.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [The Illustrated Transformer](https://jalammar.github.io/illustrated-transformer/) by Jay Alammar — the definitive visual guide to multi-head attention, positional encoding, and the full Transformer architecture. Bookmark this one.\n",
          "summary": "Multi-head attention runs parallel attention operations to capture different relationship types, while positional encodings like RoPE give the model awareness of token order.",
          "concepts": [
            "multi-head attention",
            "attention heads",
            "positional encoding",
            "RoPE",
            "ALiBi",
            "sinusoidal encoding"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
      ]
