      "title": "Transformer Architecture",
      "order_index": 2,
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "The Transformer Block",
          "slug": "transformer-block",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# The Transformer Block\n\nThe Transformer block is the repeating unit stacked to build LLMs. GPT-3 stacks 96 of them. Llama 3 70B uses 80. Understanding this single block means understanding the architecture of every modern language model.\n\n## Anatomy of a Block\n\nEach block has two sub-layers, each wrapped with a **residual connection** and **layer normalization**:\n\n```\nInput x\n  → LayerNorm → Multi-Head Self-Attention → + x (residual)\n  → LayerNorm → Feed-Forward Network       → + x (residual)\nOutput\n```\n\n```python\nclass TransformerBlock(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, d_model, n_heads, d_ff):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.ln1 = nn.LayerNorm(d_model)\n        self.attn = MultiHeadAttention(d_model, n_heads)\n        self.ln2 = nn.LayerNorm(d_model)\n        self.ffn = FeedForward(d_model, d_ff)\n\n    def forward(self, x, mask=None):\n        x = x + self.attn(self.ln1(x), mask)\n        x = x + self.ffn(self.ln2(x))\n        return x\n```\n\n## Pre-Norm vs Post-Norm\n\nThe original Transformer placed LayerNorm **after** the residual connection (post-norm). Modern LLMs use **pre-norm** — normalizing before each sub-layer. Pre-norm is more stable during training for very deep networks.\n\nSome architectures use **RMSNorm** (Root Mean Square normalization), a simplified LayerNorm that skips mean-centering and is ~10-15% faster. Llama, Mistral, and Gemma all use RMSNorm.\n\n## The Feed-Forward Network\n\nThe FFN is a position-wise MLP applied independently to each token. The original Transformer used ReLU activation, but modern LLMs have moved to **SwiGLU** (Shazeer, 2020):\n\n```\nOriginal: FFN(x) = ReLU(x·W₁ + b₁)·W₂ + b₂\nSwiGLU:   FFN(x) = (Swish(x·W₁) ⊙ (x·V))·W₂\n```\n\nSwiGLU consistently outperforms ReLU and GELU. The intermediate dimension is typically **8/3 × d_model** (rounded to a multiple of 256 for GPU efficiency).\n\n## Encoder vs Decoder Architectures\n\n| Architecture | Attention | Models | Use Case |\n|-------------|-----------|--------|----------|\n| **Encoder-only** | Bidirectional | BERT, RoBERTa | Classification, embeddings |\n| **Decoder-only** | Causal | GPT, Llama, Mistral | Generation, chat |\n| **Encoder-Decoder** | Both | T5, BART | Translation, summarization |\n\nThe LLM world has overwhelmingly converged on **decoder-only** architectures with causal attention masks.\n\n## Stacking Blocks: From Block to Model\n\nA complete LLM: Token Embedding + Positional Encoding → Transformer Block × N → LayerNorm → Linear (vocab projection) → Softmax.\n\n| Model | Blocks | d_model | Heads | Parameters |\n|-------|--------|---------|-------|------------|\n| GPT-2 Small | 12 | 768 | 12 | 124M |\n| Llama 3 8B | 32 | 4096 | 32 | 8B |\n| Llama 3 70B | 80 | 8192 | 64 | 70B |\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [But what is a GPT? Visual intro to Transformers](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wjZofJX0v4M) by 3Blue1Brown — an outstanding visual explanation of how Transformer blocks work together, from embeddings to output probabilities.\n- [Let's build GPT: from scratch, in code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kCc8FmEb1nY) by Andrej Karpathy — a 2-hour code-along that builds a working GPT from an empty file. The best way to deeply internalize the architecture.\n",
          "summary": "The Transformer block combines multi-head attention and feed-forward layers with residual connections and layer normalization — stack enough of these and you have a modern LLM.",
          "concepts": [
            "transformer block",
            "residual connections",
            "layer normalization",
            "feed-forward network",
            "SwiGLU",
            "RMSNorm"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "wjZofJX0v4M",
          "video_title": "But what is a GPT? Visual intro to Transformers | 3Blue1Brown",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Scaling Laws & Modern Architectures",
          "slug": "scaling-modern-architectures",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Scaling Laws & Modern Architectures\n\nOnce the Transformer architecture was established, the key question became: **how do you make it better?** The answer, surprisingly, has often been *simply making it bigger* — but in precise, predictable ways.\n\n## Scaling Laws\n\nKaplan et al. (2020, OpenAI) discovered that model performance follows **power laws** with respect to three variables:\n\n```\nL(N) ∝ N^(-0.076)    # N = number of parameters\nL(D) ∝ D^(-0.095)    # D = dataset size (tokens)\nL(C) ∝ C^(-0.050)    # C = compute budget (FLOPs)\n```\n\nThese are smooth, predictable curves. This allowed labs to forecast the performance of billion-dollar training runs before starting them.\n\n## Chinchilla Optimal Training\n\nHoffmann et al. (2022, DeepMind) found that most models were **undertrained** — too many parameters for the amount of data they saw. The optimal ratio is roughly **20 tokens per parameter**.\n\n| Model | Params | Tokens | Tokens/Param | Verdict |\n|-------|--------|--------|--------------|----------|\n| GPT-3 | 175B | 300B | 1.7 | Undertrained |\n| Chinchilla | 70B | 1.4T | 20 | Optimal |\n| Llama 3 | 8B | 15T | 1875 | Massively over-trained |\n\nPost-Chinchilla, the trend shifted toward **smaller models trained on more data** — more practical for deployment while matching or exceeding larger undertrained models.\n\n## Grouped-Query Attention (GQA)\n\nDuring inference, the **KV cache** (stored key-value pairs for previous tokens) becomes a memory bottleneck. **GQA** groups multiple query heads to share K/V heads:\n\n```\nMulti-Head:    Q₁K₁V₁  Q₂K₂V₂  Q₃K₃V₃  Q₄K₄V₄  (4 KV heads)\nGrouped-Query: Q₁K₁V₁  Q₂K₁V₁  Q₃K₂V₂  Q₄K₂V₂  (2 KV heads)\nMulti-Query:   Q₁K₁V₁  Q₂K₁V₁  Q₃K₁V₁  Q₄K₁V₁  (1 KV head)\n```\n\nLlama 2 70B uses 8 KV heads shared across 64 query heads — an 8× reduction in KV cache memory with minimal quality loss.\n\n## Mixture of Experts (MoE)\n\n**MoE** replaces the single FFN with multiple \"expert\" FFNs and a **router** that selects which experts process each token. Only 2 of 8 (or 2 of 64) experts activate per token, so the model has far more total parameters than it uses per forward pass.\n\nMixtral 8x7B has 47B total parameters but only ~13B active per token — massive model capacity with manageable compute. The main challenge is training the router to distribute tokens evenly (load balancing).\n\n## Flash Attention\n\nStandard attention materializes the full n×n attention matrix. For a 100K context, that's 10 billion entries. **Flash Attention** (Dao et al., 2022) restructures the computation to work in tiles that fit in GPU SRAM. The output is mathematically identical, but memory drops from O(n²) to O(n), making long-context models practical.\n\n## The Modern LLM Landscape\n\n| Family | Key Innovations | Open/Closed |\n|--------|----------------|-------------|\n| **GPT-4/4o** | MoE, massive scale | Closed |\n| **Claude** | Constitutional AI, long context | Closed |\n| **Llama 3** | GQA, massive over-training | Open weights |\n| **Mistral/Mixtral** | Sliding window attention, MoE | Open weights |\n| **Gemma** | Knowledge distillation from Gemini | Open weights |\n\nArchitectural innovations make models more efficient, while scaling laws tell us how much performance to expect from a given compute budget.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Large Language Models: A Survey](https://sebastianraschka.com/blog/2024/understanding-large-language-models.html) by Sebastian Raschka — a practical guide to modern LLM architectures, comparing design choices across model families.\n",
          "summary": "Scaling laws predict LLM performance as a function of compute, data, and parameters, while innovations like GQA, MoE, and Flash Attention make modern architectures more efficient.",
          "concepts": [
            "scaling laws",
            "Chinchilla",
            "grouped-query attention",
            "mixture of experts",
            "Flash Attention",
            "KV cache"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
