        {
          "title": "Pre-training at Scale",
          "slug": "pretraining-at-scale",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Pre-training at Scale\n\nPre-training is where an LLM acquires its knowledge and abilities — billions of parameters learning from trillions of tokens. It's the most expensive, most critical, and least understood part of the LLM pipeline.\n\n## The Data\n\nAn LLM's capabilities are bounded by its training data. Modern datasets combine multiple sources:\n\n| Source | Examples | Role |\n|--------|----------|------|\n| **Web crawl** | Common Crawl, RefinedWeb | Broad knowledge, diverse language |\n| **Books** | Books3, Project Gutenberg | Long-form reasoning, narrative |\n| **Code** | GitHub, StackOverflow | Programming, logical reasoning |\n| **Scientific papers** | arXiv, PubMed | Technical knowledge |\n| **Wikipedia** | Full dumps | Factual knowledge |\n\n**Data curation** is critical: raw Common Crawl contains spam, duplicates, toxic content, and low-quality text. Teams invest months in deduplication, quality filtering, language identification, and PII removal.\n\nLlama 3 was trained on 15 trillion tokens. For comparison, all of English Wikipedia is ~4 billion tokens — a rounding error.\n\n## Distributed Training\n\nNo single GPU can train an LLM. Training is distributed across thousands of GPUs using three parallelism strategies:\n\n**Data Parallelism**: Each GPU gets the full model but different data batches. Gradients are averaged. Simple but requires the model to fit on one GPU.\n\n**Tensor Parallelism**: Individual layers are split across GPUs — a single matrix multiplication is divided among devices. Low latency but high communication overhead.\n\n**Pipeline Parallelism**: Different layers run on different GPUs. GPU 1 runs layers 0-19, GPU 2 runs layers 20-39. Micro-batching keeps all GPUs busy.\n\nLarge runs combine all three: Llama 3 405B trained on 16,384 H100 GPUs.\n\n## Mixed Precision Training\n\n**bf16** (brain float 16) is the standard for LLM training — same exponent range as fp32, avoiding overflow issues. Most operations run in bf16, with fp32 only for numerically sensitive parts like loss accumulation.\n\n## Training Dynamics\n\nA typical pre-training run:\n\n1. **Warmup** (~2000 steps): Learning rate ramps linearly from 0 to prevent early instability.\n2. **Main training**: Learning rate decays via cosine schedule. Loss decreases smoothly following scaling laws.\n3. **Loss spikes**: Occasional sudden increases, often caused by bad data batches. Usually recoverable by rolling back a few checkpoints.\n\n## The Cost of Pre-training\n\n| Model | GPUs | Training Time | Estimated Cost |\n|-------|------|---------------|----------------|\n| Llama 2 70B | 2,048 A100s | ~35 days | ~$2M |\n| Llama 3 405B | 16,384 H100s | ~54 days | ~$30M+ |\n\nThis enormous cost is why few organizations pre-train from scratch, and why open-weight models are so valuable — they amortize the training cost across the entire community.\n",
          "summary": "Pre-training teaches LLMs language, knowledge, and reasoning from trillions of tokens using massive distributed computing across thousands of GPUs.",
          "concepts": [
            "pre-training",
            "data curation",
            "distributed training",
            "data parallelism",
            "tensor parallelism",
            "mixed precision",
            "bf16"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
