        {
          "title": "Alignment & RLHF",
          "slug": "alignment-rlhf",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Alignment & RLHF\n\nA pre-trained LLM is a powerful text predictor — but it's not a helpful assistant. It will happily complete toxic text, generate misinformation, or ignore your question to continue a Wikipedia article. **Alignment** is the process of steering a pre-trained model to be helpful, harmless, and honest.\n\n## The Alignment Problem\n\nPre-training optimizes for next-token prediction on internet text. The model learns to mimic *any* text pattern, including harmful ones. A raw pre-trained model doesn't distinguish helpful from harmful completions, will match the style of toxic prompts, and has no concept of refusing inappropriate requests.\n\n## Step 1: Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT)\n\nFine-tune the pre-trained model on high-quality (instruction, response) pairs:\n\n```json\n{\"instruction\": \"Explain photosynthesis simply\",\n \"response\": \"Plants convert sunlight, water, and CO2 into sugar and oxygen...\"}\n```\n\nSFT datasets typically contain 10K-100K carefully curated examples. The model learns to follow instructions, provide structured responses, and adopt a helpful tone. After SFT, the model follows instructions but still can be confidently wrong and hasn't learned nuanced preferences about style and safety.\n\n## Step 2: RLHF (Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback)\n\nRLHF was the technique that made ChatGPT feel qualitatively different from GPT-3. Three stages:\n\n**1. Collect comparisons**: Human annotators see two model responses to the same prompt and rank which is better. This captures nuanced preferences hard to specify in rules.\n\n**2. Train a reward model**: A separate model learns to predict human preferences — assigning higher scores to preferred responses.\n\n**3. Optimize with PPO**: Use the reward model as a signal to fine-tune the LLM via Proximal Policy Optimization, with a KL-divergence penalty to prevent drifting too far from the SFT baseline:\n\n```\nObjective = E[Reward(prompt, response)] - β · KL(π_RL || π_SFT)\n```\n\nThe KL penalty is crucial: without it, the model \"hacks\" the reward model with degenerate outputs that score high but are actually low quality.\n\n## DPO: Direct Preference Optimization\n\n**DPO** (Rafailov et al., 2023) simplifies RLHF by eliminating the separate reward model. It directly optimizes the language model on preference pairs using a clever reparameterization. DPO is simpler to implement, more stable to train, and has become the dominant alignment method for open-weight models.\n\n## Constitutional AI (CAI)\n\nAnthropic's approach: instead of collecting human comparisons for every case, define a set of **principles** (a \"constitution\") and use the AI itself to generate comparisons. The model critiques its own responses against principles like \"be helpful\", \"avoid harm\", \"be honest\", then revises them. This scales better than human annotation and makes alignment criteria explicit.\n\n## Why Alignment Is Hard\n\n- **Goodhart's Law**: Optimizing for a proxy (reward model) instead of the true goal (helpfulness) leads to reward hacking\n- **Sycophancy**: RLHF models learn to agree with users rather than correct them\n- **Specification gaming**: Models find unexpected ways to satisfy the objective without being genuinely helpful\n\nAlignment remains an active research area — the gap between \"follows instructions\" and \"genuinely beneficial\" is where much current work focuses.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [RLHF: Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback](https://huyenchip.com/2023/05/02/rlhf.html) by Chip Huyen — a practical breakdown of the RLHF pipeline with clear diagrams and honest discussion of limitations.\n- [The Alignment Problem from a Deep Learning Perspective](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2023-03-15-prompt-engineering/) by Lilian Weng — covers alignment techniques from SFT through DPO with detailed comparisons.\n",
          "summary": "Alignment transforms raw pre-trained models into helpful assistants through supervised fine-tuning and reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or direct preference optimization (DPO).",
          "concepts": [
            "alignment",
            "RLHF",
            "supervised fine-tuning",
            "reward model",
            "DPO",
            "constitutional AI"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Using LLMs Effectively",
      "order_index": 4,
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "Prompting Techniques",
          "slug": "prompting-techniques",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Prompting Techniques\n\nPrompting is how you communicate with an LLM. The difference between a mediocre and excellent result often comes down to how you frame the request — not the model's capabilities. Effective prompting is a skill that compounds with practice.\n\n## Zero-Shot Prompting\n\nThe simplest approach — just ask:\n\n```\nClassify the sentiment of this review as positive, negative, or neutral:\n\"The food was great but the service was incredibly slow.\"\nSentiment:\n```\n\nModern LLMs handle zero-shot tasks well because instruction tuning taught them to follow diverse requests.\n\n## Few-Shot Prompting\n\nProvide examples of the desired input-output behavior before the actual task:\n\n```\nClassify the sentiment:\n\nReview: \"Absolutely loved it, will come back!\"\nSentiment: Positive\n\nReview: \"Terrible experience, food was cold.\"\nSentiment: Negative\n\nReview: \"The food was great but the service was incredibly slow.\"\nSentiment:\n```\n\nLLMs are strong **in-context learners** — they infer the pattern from examples and apply it. 3-5 examples usually suffice. Use diverse examples that cover edge cases, and put the most representative ones last (recency bias).\n\n## Chain-of-Thought (CoT)\n\nFor reasoning tasks, asking the model to **show its work** dramatically improves accuracy:\n\n```\nQ: A store has 3 shelves with 8 books each and 2 shelves with 5 books.\n   How many books total?\n\nA: Let me work through this step by step.\n- 3 shelves x 8 books = 24 books\n- 2 shelves x 5 books = 10 books\n- Total: 24 + 10 = 34 books\n```\n\nThe phrase **\"Let's think step by step\"** can trigger CoT reasoning even without examples (zero-shot CoT). This simple addition improved GSM8K math accuracy from ~18% to ~79% in the original paper.\n\n## System Prompts\n\nSystem prompts set the model's persona, constraints, and behavior:\n\n```\nSystem: You are a concise technical writer. Answer questions about\nPython in 2-3 sentences maximum. Include a code example when relevant.\nDo not add disclaimers or caveats.\n```\n\nEffective system prompts are **specific** about format, tone, length, and constraints. Vague instructions like \"be helpful\" add nothing.\n\n## Structured Output\n\nFor reliable integration with code, constrain the output format:\n\n```\nExtract these fields from the text as JSON:\n- name (string)\n- age (integer)\n- occupation (string)\n\nText: \"Dr. Sarah Chen, 42, is a neurosurgeon at Mass General.\"\n```\n\nMost API providers now support **JSON mode** or **function calling** that guarantees valid structured output.\n\n## Common Pitfalls\n\n- **Ambiguity**: \"Summarize this\" — how long? What focus? For what audience?\n- **Overloading**: Cramming multiple complex tasks into one prompt. Break them up.\n- **Negative instructions**: \"Don't mention X\" is less reliable than \"Focus on Y\".\n- **Missing context**: The model doesn't know what you know. Be explicit.\n\n## Prompting vs Fine-tuning\n\n| | Prompting | Fine-tuning |\n|--|-----------|-------------|\n| **Cost** | Free (just tokens) | GPU hours + data |\n| **Iteration speed** | Seconds | Hours/days |\n| **Customization** | Moderate | Deep |\n| **Best for** | General tasks, prototyping | Domain-specific, production |\n\nStart with prompting. If you can't get the quality you need after serious prompt engineering, that's when fine-tuning becomes worthwhile.\n",
          "summary": "Prompting techniques like few-shot examples, chain-of-thought reasoning, and structured system prompts dramatically affect LLM output quality without any model changes.",
          "concepts": [
            "zero-shot prompting",
            "few-shot prompting",
            "chain-of-thought",
            "system prompts",
            "structured output",
            "in-context learning"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "RAG & Retrieval-Augmented Generation",
          "slug": "rag-retrieval",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# RAG & Retrieval-Augmented Generation\n\nLLMs have impressive knowledge, but it's frozen at training time, can hallucinate confidently, and doesn't include your private data. **RAG** bridges this gap by giving the model access to external knowledge at inference time.\n\n## Why LLMs Hallucinate\n\nLLMs generate text based on statistical patterns — they don't \"know\" facts the way a database does. When uncertain, they produce plausible-sounding text rather than admitting ignorance. RAG reduces hallucination by grounding responses in retrieved source documents.\n\n## The RAG Pipeline\n\n```\nUser Query → Embed → Search Vector DB → Retrieve Top-K Chunks\n           → Augment Prompt with Context → LLM Generates Answer\n```\n\n### Step 1: Document Ingestion\n\nSplit documents into chunks and convert to embeddings:\n\n```python\nfrom langchain.text_splitter import RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter\n\nsplitter = RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter(\n    chunk_size=512, chunk_overlap=50\n)\nchunks = splitter.split_documents(documents)\n```\n\n### Step 2: Embedding & Indexing\n\nConvert chunks to vectors using an embedding model and store in a **vector database**:\n\n```python\nfrom langchain.embeddings import OpenAIEmbeddings\nfrom langchain.vectorstores import Chroma\n\nembeddings = OpenAIEmbeddings(model=\"text-embedding-3-small\")\nvectorstore = Chroma.from_documents(chunks, embeddings)\n```\n\n### Step 3: Retrieval\n\nEmbed the user's query and find the most similar chunks via **cosine similarity**. Semantically similar text ends up close in embedding space — \"cardiac arrest\" matches \"heart attack\" even without lexical overlap.\n\n```python\nresults = vectorstore.similarity_search(query, k=5)\n```\n\n### Step 4: Generation\n\nStuff retrieved chunks into the LLM's prompt as context:\n\n```\nContext:\n[Retrieved chunk 1]\n[Retrieved chunk 2]\n\nBased on the context above, answer: {user_question}\n```\n\n## Chunking Strategies\n\nHow you split documents matters enormously:\n\n| Strategy | Description | Best For |\n|----------|-------------|----------|\n| **Fixed size** | Split every N characters | Simple, fast |\n| **Recursive** | Split by paragraphs, then sentences | General purpose |\n| **Semantic** | Split at topic boundaries | Complex documents |\n| **Document structure** | Split by headers, sections | Markdown, HTML, PDFs |\n\n**Chunk size tradeoffs**: Too small (100 tokens) → fragments lose context. Too large (2000 tokens) → dilutes relevance. 300-800 tokens is the sweet spot.\n\n## RAG vs Fine-tuning\n\n| | RAG | Fine-tuning |\n|--|-----|-------------|\n| **Knowledge updates** | Instant (update docs) | Retrain required |\n| **Source attribution** | Easy (cite chunks) | Not possible |\n| **Hallucination** | Reduced (grounded) | Still possible |\n| **Private data** | Stays in your DB | Baked into weights |\n| **Reasoning depth** | Limited by context | Internalized |\n\nMany production systems combine both: fine-tune for domain style and reasoning, then use RAG for factual grounding.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Retrieval-Augmented Generation for Knowledge-Intensive NLP Tasks](https://arxiv.org/abs/2005.11401) (Lewis et al., 2020) — the original RAG paper that formalized the retrieve-then-generate approach.\n",
          "summary": "RAG reduces LLM hallucination by retrieving relevant documents from a vector database and injecting them into the prompt as grounding context.",
          "concepts": [
            "retrieval-augmented generation",
            "vector database",
            "embeddings",
            "chunking",
            "cosine similarity",
            "hallucination"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Fine-tuning & Evaluation",
      "order_index": 5,
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "LoRA & Parameter-Efficient Methods",
          "slug": "lora-parameter-efficient",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# LoRA & Parameter-Efficient Methods\n\nPre-trained LLMs are general-purpose, but many applications need specialized behavior — a medical assistant, a code reviewer, a customer support bot. Full fine-tuning adjusts all parameters, but for a 70B model that requires hundreds of gigabytes of GPU memory. **Parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT)** achieves similar results by training less than 1% of parameters.\n\n## The Cost Problem\n\nFull fine-tuning of a 7B model requires storing model weights (~14 GB in fp16), gradients (~14 GB), and AdamW optimizer states (~56 GB) — totaling ~84 GB, requiring multiple high-end GPUs. For a 70B model, multiply by 10.\n\n## LoRA: Low-Rank Adaptation\n\n**LoRA** (Hu et al., 2021) is based on a key insight: weight changes during fine-tuning have **low intrinsic rank**. Instead of updating the full weight matrix W (d × k parameters), decompose the update into two small matrices:\n\n```\nW' = W + ΔW = W + B·A\n```\n\nwhere **A** (r × k) and **B** (d × r), with rank r << min(d, k). The original weights **W are frozen**; only A and B are trained.\n\nFor d=k=4096 and r=16: full fine-tuning trains 16.7M parameters per layer; LoRA trains 131K — a **128× reduction**. At inference, merge B·A back into W for **zero additional latency**.\n\n```python\nfrom peft import LoraConfig, get_peft_model\n\nconfig = LoraConfig(\n    r=16,\n    lora_alpha=32,\n    target_modules=[\"q_proj\", \"k_proj\", \"v_proj\", \"o_proj\"],\n    lora_dropout=0.05,\n)\nmodel = get_peft_model(model, config)\nmodel.print_trainable_parameters()\n# trainable: 0.1% of total parameters\n```\n\n## QLoRA: Fine-tuning 70B on a Single GPU\n\n**QLoRA** (Dettmers et al., 2023) combines LoRA with 4-bit quantization of the base model. Base model memory drops to ~3.5 GB for 7B, enabling fine-tuning on a single 24 GB consumer GPU.\n\n```python\nfrom transformers import BitsAndBytesConfig\n\nbnb_config = BitsAndBytesConfig(\n    load_in_4bit=True,\n    bnb_4bit_quant_type=\"nf4\",\n    bnb_4bit_compute_dtype=torch.bfloat16,\n    bnb_4bit_use_double_quant=True,\n)\n```\n\n## Which Layers to Adapt?\n\nResearch and practice have converged on adapting attention projections: **Q and V** as the minimum effective set, adding **K and O** for meaningful improvement. Higher rank r captures more signal — r=8-16 for most tasks, r=64 for complex domain shifts.\n\n## Other PEFT Methods\n\n| Method | How It Works | Trainable % | Inference Cost |\n|--------|-------------|-------------|----------------|\n| **LoRA** | Low-rank weight updates | ~0.1% | None (merged) |\n| **QLoRA** | LoRA + 4-bit quantization | ~0.1% | None (merged) |\n| **Adapters** | Small FFNs between layers | ~1-5% | Added latency |\n| **Prefix Tuning** | Trainable tokens in K/V | ~0.1% | Minor |\n| **Prompt Tuning** | Soft learned embeddings | <0.01% | Minor |\n\nLoRA/QLoRA have become the de facto standard due to the quality-efficiency tradeoff and zero inference overhead after merging.\n",
          "summary": "LoRA enables fine-tuning large LLMs by training low-rank decompositions of weight updates, achieving near full fine-tuning quality with less than 1% of trainable parameters.",
          "concepts": [
            "LoRA",
            "QLoRA",
            "parameter-efficient fine-tuning",
            "low-rank adaptation",
            "quantization",
            "adapter methods"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Evaluation & Benchmarks",
          "slug": "evaluation-benchmarks",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Evaluation & Benchmarks\n\nHow do you know if one LLM is better than another? For classification, metrics like accuracy or F1 are straightforward. For open-ended text generation, evaluation is one of the hardest unsolved problems in AI.\n\n## Why LLM Evaluation Is Hard\n\nTraditional ML evaluation compares predictions against ground truth. But for \"Write a poem about autumn\" or \"Explain quantum computing\", there's no single correct answer. Quality is subjective, multidimensional (accuracy, fluency, helpfulness, safety, creativity), and context-dependent.\n\n## Benchmark Suites\n\nStandardized benchmarks measure specific capabilities:\n\n| Benchmark | What It Tests | Format |\n|-----------|--------------|--------|\n| **MMLU** | Broad knowledge (57 subjects) | Multiple choice |\n| **HumanEval** | Code generation | Write Python functions |\n| **GSM8K** | Grade school math | Word problems |\n| **HellaSwag** | Common sense reasoning | Sentence completion |\n| **TruthfulQA** | Resistance to misconceptions | Open-ended + MC |\n| **MT-Bench** | Multi-turn conversation | LLM-as-judge scoring |\n| **MATH** | Competition-level math | Problem solving |\n\n**Aggregate leaderboards** like the Open LLM Leaderboard combine multiple benchmarks, but should be read critically — models can be optimized for benchmarks at the expense of real-world performance.\n\n## LLM-as-Judge\n\nUsing a strong LLM (like GPT-4) to evaluate another model's outputs has become standard practice. It scales well, correlates reasonably with human judgments, and can evaluate nuanced qualities. **Pairwise comparison** (\"which response is better?\") tends to be more reliable than absolute scoring.\n\nRisks: biased toward verbose responses, may share blind spots with the evaluated model.\n\n## Human Evaluation\n\nThe gold standard remains human evaluation:\n\n- **Chatbot Arena** (lmsys.org): Users chat with two anonymous models and vote for the better one. Produces **Elo ratings** — the most trusted LLM ranking. Over 1M human votes and counting.\n- **Domain expert evaluation**: For medical, legal, or code tasks, only domain experts can meaningfully assess quality.\n\n## Contamination & Benchmark Gaming\n\nModels may have **seen benchmark data** during pre-training. If GSM8K problems appear in Common Crawl, a model might \"memorize\" answers rather than demonstrate reasoning.\n\nMitigation: use held-out test sets, create dynamic benchmarks that refresh regularly, and check for suspiciously high scores on public vs private equivalents.\n\n## Red Teaming\n\n**Red teaming** probes failure modes — trying to elicit harmful, biased, or incorrect outputs:\n\n- **Jailbreaking**: Circumventing safety guardrails\n- **Bias detection**: Testing for demographic biases\n- **Factual probing**: Finding confident hallucination topics\n- **Adversarial inputs**: Edge cases causing unexpected behavior\n\n## Building Your Own Evaluation\n\nFor production systems, generic benchmarks aren't enough:\n\n1. Collect real user queries (or realistic synthetic ones)\n2. Define rubrics with clear criteria specific to your task\n3. Combine automated + human evaluation: LLM-as-judge for volume, human review for calibration\n4. Track regressions: re-run your eval suite when you update prompts, models, or RAG pipelines\n\nThe best evaluation is one you'll actually run consistently. Start simple, iterate.\n",
          "summary": "LLM evaluation uses a combination of standardized benchmarks, LLM-as-judge scoring, human evaluation, and red teaming to assess model capabilities across multiple dimensions.",
          "concepts": [
            "benchmarks",
            "MMLU",
            "HumanEval",
            "LLM-as-judge",
            "Chatbot Arena",
            "red teaming",
            "contamination"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
